1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,530
At a homecoming celebration last year, I met a college friend whom I had not seen for ten years.

2
00:00:06,719 --> 00:00:11,170
Chuck was a very bright student and was graduated with honors.

3
00:00:11,360 --> 00:00:16,769
His goal when I last saw him was to own his own business in western Nebraska.

4
00:00:17,120 --> 00:00:21,170
I asked Chuck what kind of business he finally established.

5
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:26,209
Well, he confessed, I didn't go into business for myself.

6
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:31,009
I wouldn't have said this to anyone five years ago or even one year ago,

7
00:00:31,120 --> 00:00:33,330
but now I'm ready to talk about it.

8
00:00:33,680 --> 00:00:41,890
As I look back at my college education now, I see that I became an expert in why a business idea won't work out.

9
00:00:42,080 --> 00:00:47,650
I learned every conceivable pitfall, every reason why a small business will fail.

10
00:00:47,760 --> 00:00:49,729
You've got to have ample capital.

11
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:52,209
Be sure the business cycle is right.

12
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:54,930
Is there a big demand for what you will offer?

13
00:00:55,040 --> 00:00:57,410
Is local industry stabilized?

14
00:00:57,600 --> 00:01:00,130
A thousand and one things to check out.

15
00:01:00,560 --> 00:01:04,690
The thing that hurts most is that several of my old high school friends,

16
00:01:04,719 --> 00:01:08,610
who never seemed to have much on the ball and didn't even go to college,

17
00:01:08,800 --> 00:01:11,729
now are very well established in their own businesses.

18
00:01:11,920 --> 00:01:12,690
But me?

19
00:01:12,800 --> 00:01:16,370
I'm just plodding along, auditing freight shipments.

20
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:21,090
Had I been drilled a little more in why a small business can succeed,

21
00:01:21,199 --> 00:01:23,890
I'd be better off in every way today.

22
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:31,729
The thinking that guided Chuck's intelligence was a lot more important than the amount of Chuck's intelligence.

23
00:01:32,160 --> 00:01:35,249
Why some brilliant people are failures.

24
00:01:35,600 --> 00:01:40,370
I've been close for many years to a person who qualifies as a genius,

25
00:01:40,479 --> 00:01:44,690
has high abstract intelligence, and is Phi Beta Kappa.

26
00:01:44,880 --> 00:01:51,170
Despite this very high native intelligence, he is one of the most unsuccessful people I know.

27
00:01:51,360 --> 00:01:53,330
He has a very mediocre job.

28
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:55,330
He's afraid of responsibility.

29
00:01:55,520 --> 00:01:56,769
He has never married.

30
00:01:56,959 --> 00:01:59,489
Lots of marriages end in divorce.

31
00:01:59,760 --> 00:02:01,170
He has few friends.

32
00:02:01,360 --> 00:02:02,690
People bore him.

33
00:02:02,959 --> 00:02:05,729
He's never invested in property of any kind.

34
00:02:05,840 --> 00:02:07,410
He might lose his money.

35
00:02:07,760 --> 00:02:13,009
This man uses his great brain power to prove why things won't work,

36
00:02:13,040 --> 00:02:17,570
rather than directing his mental power to searching for ways to succeed.

37
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:26,290
Because of the negative thinking that guides his great reservoir of brains, this fellow contributes little and creates nothing.

38
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:30,290
With a changed attitude, he could do great things indeed.

39
00:02:30,479 --> 00:02:35,330
He has the brains to be a tremendous success, but not the thought power.

40
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:41,890
Another person I know well was inducted into the Army shortly after earning a Ph.D.

